		<description><![CDATA[In episode two of the All Indie Writers Podcast, I put up a copy of Alicia Rades' new e-book for a giveaway. Anyone sending me a question about blogging to be answered in a future podcast episode would be entered in a drawing, and one person would win a copy. I promised the results would be posted today, so here [&#8230;]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>In <a href="http://allindiewriters.com/podcast/2/">episode two</a> of the All Indie Writers Podcast, I put up a copy of Alicia Rades' new e-book for a giveaway. Anyone sending me a question about blogging to be answered in a future podcast episode would be entered in a drawing, and one person would win a copy.</p>
<p>I promised the results would be posted today, so here you go:</p>
<h2>The Winner(s)</h2>
<p>Only three people sent in questions for the giveaway. They were:</p>
<ul>
<li>Anne Wayman</li>
<li>KeriLynn Engel</li>
<li>Emily Fowler</li>
</ul>
<p>Because of that, I changed my mind on the drawing. Instead, because there were so few entries, I decided to buy them <em>all </em>a copy of Alicia's e-book. And I hope they enjoy it as much as I did.</p>
<h2>Lessons Learned</h2>
<p>At first I was disappointed by the low number of entries. But I learned a few things along the way. And as I've said before, learning is a huge benefit of failure, and if you never fail you probably aren't taking enough risks. We all make mistakes, and I hope that by sharing some of mine others can learn from them too. Here's where I went wrong:</p>
<ul>
<li>I did the giveaway much too early. At only the second episode of the podcast, there simply wasn't a large enough following for something like this yet.</li>
<li>I don't think I gave people enough time. The podcast released last Thursday, and the deadline was the following Monday. Next time I'll run the giveaway over either one or two weeks to give people a chance to catch up on the episode. Rushing it was a mistake.</li>
<li>My podcast feed was broken, so subscribers didn't even receive notice that the second episode went live. In this case, the broken feed itself wasn't my fault. The account is set up for podcasting. And the individual track was set to be included in the feed. Where I <em>am </em>at fault is in not checking on the feed sooner. I figured I'd give it a few hours to update, but took a couple of days to actually check up on it, only after I saw a 75% drop in listeners. Something's screwy with SoundCloud's RSS feed and updates aren't being fed to Feedburner or iTunes. So if you subscribed after the first episode and didn't hear about the second, I apologize. I've contacted Soundcloud and am still waiting on a solution to the problem. In the meantime, you can access the episode <a href="http://allindiewriters.com/podcast/2/">here</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>If you missed the giveaway period but you still have a blogging-related question you'd like me to answer, please send it to <a href="mailto:jenn@allindiewriters.com">jenn@allindiewriters.com</a> (include the word "Podcast" in the subject line somewhere). Episode four, which will be released on December 4th, will be a special Q&amp;A episode where I'll answer blogging-related questions that have come in. Between giveaway entries and a question received a bit late for that, I'm up to five so far. They're a great mix, and it should make for a great episode for new and experienced bloggers alike.</p>
<p>In the meantime, I hope you'll hang in there with me through the feed problems while I work with <a href="http://princessjones.com">Princess Jones</a> on the November 20th episode about dealing with negative book reviews. I'm looking forward to it, and I hope you are too.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
