				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It's that time again! NaNoWriMo kicked off over the weekend, and writers everywhere are challenging themselves to write novels of at least 50k words during November.</p>
<p>I'm taking part again, and like last year I'll document my progress here at All Indie Writers (you can keep an eye on my word count progress in the sidebar, and I'll occasionally post updates or any tips or tricks I pick up along the way).</p>
<h2>Free Tools for NaNoWriMo Authors</h2>
<p>Now is the perfect time for a quick reminder about the free tools I have available for NaNoWriMo authors. So if you're looking for ways to track your progress, give these tools a try:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://allindiewriters.com/forums/section/monthly-writing-challenges/monthly-word-count-goal-challenge/">Monthly Word Count Challenge Forum</a> -- This is a section of my writing forums devoted to monthly word count challenges. Given that NaNo is a great example of that, it's a perfect place to share your progress and seek feedback from your fellow authors.</li>
<li><a href="http://allindiewriters.com/forums/topic/monthly-word-count-goal-challenge-introduction/">Monthly Word Count Tracker / Calendar</a> -- This is a downloadable calendar you can print out and hang on your wall to keep track of your daily progress.</li>
<li><a href="http://allindiewriters.com/wordcount-tracker/">Word Count Tracker (Simple)</a> -- This is an online word count tracker you can use to add a progress bar to your website or blog.</li>
<li><a href="http://allindiewriters.com/word-count-tracker/">Word Count Tracker (Advanced)</a> -- This is another online word count tracker that lets you add a progress bar to your website or blog. While it has more customization options (such as tracking things other than word counts), for NaNo you'll probably just want to stick to the basics.</li>
</ul>
<h2>My NaNoWriMo Plan for 2014</h2>
<p>I mentioned previously that I would be working on a horror novel for NaNoWriMo this year (a ghost story), and that I would be using The Snowflake Method to prepare (my first time using it). I made it through the scene list portion of the Snowflake plan, though I didn't flesh out more detailed descriptions of each scene. While not ideal for my first go-around, I'm pretty confident that the scene list and four-page synopsis are going to help me through this first draft.</p>
<p>This project is a little more daunting than last year's mystery novel because the story hasn't played itself out in my head a million times like last year's story had by the time NaNo came along.</p>
<p>This year I'm taking a tiered word count approach just like last year. That's where I start with my highest word count goals and step them down each week to ease off on the pressure before Thanksgiving. I don't plan to write at all for the last four days of the month (Thanksgiving, Black Friday, and the following weekend which is when I do the bulk of my Christmas decorating and shopping).</p>
<p>I'm also leaving my weekends free. Last year I only scheduled myself to take off on Sundays, so that's going to be a big difference this year, losing several more writing days.</p>
<p>While my goal is to not work on my NaNo project at all on the weekends, I'm also considering them flexible time if I need it. For example, if I don't feel well and want to take a Wednesday off, I'll do that and make up the word count on Saturday if I can't split it among my other scheduled writing days for the week.</p>
<p>Today is my first writing day, and it has the biggest word count goal of 5000 words. That's 10% of my monthly target scheduled to be knocked out in a day. I'm nearly finished with the rest of today's work, so I'm looking forward to jumping in. Normally I would knock out my NaNo word count first thing in the morning, but I worked late finishing up the scene list, so I'm operating on a late start today.</p>
<p>My daily targets drop to 4000 words per day tomorrow through Friday, so by the end of my first week, I should be nearly halfway to my 50k word target. Next week it drops to 3000 words per day, then 2000 words per day, with my final week splitting the last 4000 words across my final three writing days. This approach worked very well for me last year, so I'm hoping for a similar outcome.</p>
<p>Who else is taking part in NaNoWriMo this month? What's your plan to reach 50k words? Do you set daily targets or just write as much as you can when you're able to? Are you an outliner or a pantser? Share your NaNo history and hopes for this year in the comments.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
